MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Driving a real busybox defconfig through an in-process box make surfaced a hard
kati bug: a self-feeding pattern rule (Kbuild's `$(obj)/%: $(src)/%_shipped`)
recursed forever — fixdep.c → fixdep.c_shipped → fixdep.c_shipped_shipped → … —
until the stack overflowed and aborted the engine. Diagnosed by adding a
recursion guard that named the runaway target instead of crashing.

Root cause + fix (GNU make's "no pattern rule is used more than once in a chain
of implicit rules"): can_pick_implicit_rule's prerequisite lookahead counted the
SAME rule as a producer of its own prerequisite, so the chain never terminated.
has_producing_rule_except now excludes the current rule's own output patterns
from that lookahead. Because the real shipped file (e.g. fixdep.c_shipped) EXISTS
on disk, the target still builds from it — the chain just stops, exactly like
GNU make.

That fix unmasked a second bug: exists() checked the target relative to the
engine's PROCESS cwd, not the make's working_dir, so the shipped-file existence
check failed in a box and the now-correct chain was wrongly rejected
("No rule to make target zconf.tab.c"). exists() now resolves against
ev.working_dir (same class as the CURDIR fix).

Backstops (turn a crash into a graceful, named error): a per-thread eval
recursion guard (expr.rs) and dependency recursion guard (dep.rs). Plus 64 MiB
worker stacks on the box brush tokio runtime and the n2 recipe runtime, so deep
(but finite) recursion on large Makefiles doesn't overflow.

Result: `make defconfig` builds the kconfig tooling (gcc-compiled) and runs it
fully in-process, writing a valid .config (1078 lines, 875 applets). Corpus
stays 364/378 fail=0; parallel-equiv 364/364.

